<protolog id="rid.3225_nm.410" type="description" xmlns="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog file:/C:/NamesforLife/workspace/namesforlife-schema/protolog.xsd"><organism doi="10.1601/nm.410" rank="genus">Ferroglobus</organism><reference id="rid.3225"><citation citation-type="journal"><authors><person-name><surname>Hafenbradl</surname><given-names>D.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Keller</surname><given-names>M.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Dirmeier</surname><given-names>R.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Rachel</surname><given-names>R.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Roßnagel</surname><given-names>P.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Burggraf</surname><given-names>S.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Huber</surname><given-names>H.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Stetter</surname><given-names>K.O.</given-names></person-name></authors><article-title>Ferroglobus placidus gen. nov., sp. nov., A novel hyperthermophilic archaeum that oxidizes Fe2+ at neutral pH under anoxic conditions.</article-title><year>1996</year><volume>166</volume><fpage>308</fpage><lpage>314</lpage><source id="118">Archives of Microbiology</source><abbrev>Arch Microbiol</abbrev><issn>0302-8933</issn><essn>1432-072X</essn><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1007/s002030050388</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">8929276</pub-id></citation></reference><content><p class="title"><s>Description of <i>Ferroglobus</i> gen. nov.</s></p><p class="etymology"><s><i>Ferroglobus</i> (Fer. ro. glo' bus. L. n. <i>ferrum</i>, iron; L. masc. n. <i>globus</i>, ball; L. masc. n. <i>Ferroglobus</i>, the iron ball)</s></p><p class="description"><s>Cells irregular coccoid, 0.7–1.3 μm in diameter.</s><s>Weak, blue-green fluorescence at 420 nm.</s><s>Optimal growth at approximately 85°C, pH 7.0, and 2% NaCl.</s><s>Motile by monopolar flagella.</s><s>Strictly anaerobic.</s><s>Chemolithoautotroph or heterotroph.</s><s>Growth on Fe(II), S<sup>2–</sup> or H<sub>2</sub> as electron donor and nitrate as electron acceptor, and in the presence of H<sub>2</sub>, also with S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub><sup>2–</sup> as electron acceptor.</s><s>Slayer envelope.</s><s>Membrane contains phytanyl ether lipids.</s><s>G+C content approximately 43 mol%.</s><s>By phylogenetic analysis of the 16S rRNA sequence, a member of the <i>Archaeoglobales</i>.</s><s>Habitat: marine hydrothermal systems</s></p></content></protolog>